I"<p>Let’s see how far can we get using hebrew:</p>

<p>First good sign comes from NLTK, running the command:</p>

<div class="language-python highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code><span class="o">&gt;&gt;&gt;</span> <span class="n">nltk</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">corpus</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">udhr</span><span class="p">.</span><span class="n">fileids</span><span class="p">()</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>returns as part of it’s output:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>'Hebrew_Ivrit-Hebrew', 'Hebrew_Ivrit-UTF8'
</code></pre></div></div>

<p>But sadly, the API chosen at the beginning does not provide a bible in Hebrew.</p>

<p>For a site that provides so wide a variety of bible versions in several languages, there must be a very good set of reasons as for why Hebrew is not present; I can only blame myself for not checking that while picking a source.</p>

<p>With the purpose of finding a way to make the basic analysis in Hebrew, here’s some interesting findings:</p>

<ul>
  <li><a href="https://github.com/openscriptures/morphhb">https://github.com/openscriptures/morphhb</a></li>
</ul>

<p>Other API produces the following:</p>

<p><a href="https://getbible.net/json?passage=GEN1:1&amp;version=wlc"></a></p>

